===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|fr|abatis}}, {{m|fr|abattis|t=mass of things beaten or cut down}}, from {{m|fr|abattre}}. See {{m|en|abate}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈæb.əˌtiː/}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|en|/ˈæb.əˌti/|/ˈæb.ə.tɪs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|abatis|+}}

# A means of defense formed by felled trees, or sometimes by bent trees, the ends of whose branches are [[sharpened]] and directed outwards, or against the enemy, and more recently fortified with barbed wire. {{defdate|Mid 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref>
# {{lb|en|historical}} In the [[Middle Ages]], an officer of the stables who had the care of measuring out the provender; an [[avenor]].
# In coal-mining, walls of cord-wood piled up crosswise to keep the underground roads open so as to secure ventilation.

